.\" Man page for mulberry(1)
.TH MULBERRY 1 "May 2026" "4.2a1" "Mulberry Email Client"
.SH NAME
mulberry \- Internet email and calendar client
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B mulberry
.RB [ \-h | \-\-help ]
.RB [ \-v | \-\-version ]
.RB [ "\-D \fIdirectory\fR" ]
.RB [ "\-p \fIfile\fR" ]
.RB [ "\-u \fIurl\fR" ]
.RB [ \-d | \-\-disconnect ]
.RB [ \-\-plugins
.IR directory ]
.RB [ \-\-extras
.IR directory ]
.RI [ "mailto:" ... ]
.RI [ "webcal:" ... ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B Mulberry
is a standards-focused desktop email and calendaring client
supporting IMAP4rev1, POP3, SMTP, CalDAV, CardDAV, LDAP, SIEVE,
ManageSieve, S/MIME, and PGP. It emphasizes server-side operations
\(em searching, sorting, filtering, and threading happen on the
server rather than locally.
.PP
Mulberry supports multiple accounts and identities, IMAP ACLs for
shared folders, a GUI for server-side Sieve filtering, offline
mail caching, and calendar/address book synchronization via CalDAV
and CardDAV.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print a summary of command-line options and exit.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-version
Print the version number and exit.
.TP
.BI \-D " directory"
Set the location for the
.I .mulberry
directory, which stores default preferences and local mailbox data.
The default is the user's home directory, resulting in
.IR ~/.mulberry/ .
.TP
.BI \-p " file"
Use the specified preferences file on startup instead of the default
.IR ~/.mulberry/preferences.mbp .
.TP
.BI \-u " url"
Open the specified mailto URL and create a draft message on startup.
Equivalent to passing a bare
.B mailto:
URL as an argument.
.TP
.BR \-d ", " \-\-disconnect
Prompt to start in disconnected (offline) mode, even if not
already configured to do so.
.TP
.BI \-\-plugins " directory"
Override the default location for Mulberry plugin shared libraries.
The default is
.IR /usr/lib/mulberry/Plug\-ins/ .
.TP
.BI \-\-extras " directory"
Specify an alternate location for
.IR mailcap ,
.IR mime.types ,
and
.I url.helpers
files.
.SH URL ARGUMENTS
If a bare
.B mailto:
or
.B webcal:
URL is passed as an argument (without the
.B \-u
flag), Mulberry opens it directly. This allows desktop environments
to use Mulberry as the default handler for email and calendar URLs:
.PP
.RS
.nf
mulberry "mailto:user@example.com?subject=Hello"
mulberry "webcal://example.com/calendar.ics"
.fi
.RE
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B PRINTCMD
The default print command shown in the print dialog.
.TP
.B PAPERSIZE
The default paper size for printing. Allowed values:
.BR USLetter ", " USLegal ", " USExecutive ", " A4Letter ", " B5Letter .
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.mulberry/
Default directory for preferences, local mailboxes, offline caches,
address books, and calendar data.
.TP
.I ~/.mulberry/preferences.mbp
Default preferences file.
.TP
.I ~/.mulberry/Recover_Drafts/
Auto-saved draft messages for crash recovery.
.TP
.I /usr/lib/mulberry/Plug\-ins/
Authentication, security, and address book import plugins.
.TP
.I /usr/lib/mulberry/Resources/
Application resource files (icons, string tables, timezone data).
.SH PROTOCOLS
.TP
.B IMAP4rev1
Remote mailbox access with server-side searching, sorting,
threading, and filtering. Supports IDLE, BINARY, COMPRESS=DEFLATE,
SPECIAL-USE, MULTIAPPEND, REPLACE, NAMESPACE, UIDPLUS, ACL, QUOTA,
SORT, THREAD, LIST-EXTENDED, LIST-STATUS, SEARCHRES, ESEARCH/ESORT,
APPENDLIMIT, STATUS=SIZE, and many other extensions. All 15
mandatory IMAP4rev2 extensions are supported.
.TP
.B POP3
Mailbox download with optional leave-on-server, timed deletion,
and size limits.
.TP
.B SMTP
Message submission on port 587 with STARTTLS, AUTH (PLAIN, LOGIN,
CRAM-MD5, DIGEST-MD5, GSSAPI, Kerberos), PIPELINING, 8BITMIME,
ENHANCEDSTATUSCODES, DSN, and SIZE support. Asynchronous send queue
with automatic retry on temporary failures.
.TP
.B CalDAV
Calendar synchronization, event/task management, free/busy lookup,
and scheduling (iTIP) via WebDAV.
.TP
.B CardDAV
Contact synchronization and address book management via WebDAV.
.TP
.B LDAP
Directory service lookups for address completion and searching.
.TP
.B IMSP / ACAP
Remote preferences and address book storage.
.TP
.B ManageSieve
Server-side mail filtering with GUI script editor supporting
reject, fileinto, vacation, relational, and imap4flags extensions.
.TP
.B S/MIME
Message signing and encryption using AES-128-CBC, with certificate
management and verification.
.TP
.B PGP/GPG
Message signing (SHA-256) and encryption via plugin architecture.
.SH EXTERNAL EDITOR
Mulberry supports using an external text editor for composing drafts.
Configure the editor command in Preferences > Outgoing > Editor.
Use
.B %s
as a placeholder for the temporary file path:
.PP
.RS
.nf
emacs %s
gvim -f %s
.fi
.RE
.PP
Mulberry writes the draft text to a temporary file, spawns the editor
process, and waits for it to exit. On exit, the temporary file is
read back and replaces the draft text. The editor must run in the
foreground (note the
.B \-f
flag for gvim).
.SH DEBUGGING OPTIONS
These options are primarily useful for developers:
.TP
.B \-\-gdb
Enable verbose assertion output and X11 debugging. Equivalent to
.B \-assert\-print
combined with
.BR \-xassert .
.TP
.B \-assert\-print
Print assertion failures to stderr instead of showing a dialog.
.TP
.B \-assert\-ask
Show an interactive dialog on assertion failures.
.TP
.B \-assert\-abort
Call abort() on assertion failures (for core dumps).
.TP
.B \-xassert
Enable X11/JX toolkit debugging output.
